# .trivyignore — hermes-agent / hermes-agent-dev (context: apps/hermes-agent)
# Added 2026-07-18 after the first hermes-agent scan (run 29650965148)
# gated red. Trivy false positives — investigated, not silenced blindly.
#
# CVE-2022-25235 / CVE-2022-25236 (expat, bundled in the "firefox"
# package): the exact false positive already documented in
# apps/firefox/.trivyignore — this image installs Firefox for the
# dashboard kiosk via the same packages.mozilla.org repo + apt-pin
# pattern. Trivy's Ubuntu OS-package DB tracks vulnerabilities for the
# distro's own "firefox" package, which since Ubuntu 22.04+ is a
# transitional stub that just installs the snap, versioned
# "1:1snap1-0ubuntu1" — the epoch (1:) makes it dpkg-compare as newer
# than ANY real Mozilla .deb build (ours has version scheme
# "<version>~buildN", no epoch), so Trivy always reports our real,
# up-to-date Firefox as vulnerable to these two 2022 CVEs.
# Documented, reproduced elsewhere: aquasecurity/trivy discussion #6792
# (https://github.com/aquasecurity/trivy/discussions/6792).
#
# Re-evaluate if Trivy changes how it resolves third-party .deb Firefox
# builds, or if these CVE IDs start showing up with a different
# (non-snap) fixed version. Keep in sync with apps/firefox/.trivyignore
# and apps/devtools/.trivyignore — all three carry this same pair.
CVE-2022-25235
CVE-2022-25236

# ----------------------------------------------------------------------
# Accepted upstream-owned findings — NOT false positives. Unlike the
# expat pair above, the six IDs below are real vulnerabilities, in
# Python dependencies resolved by the upstream Hermes installer
# (hermes-agent.nousresearch.com/install.sh --branch v2026.7.7.2).
# Added 2026-07-20 after run 29711725457 gated red.
#
# Why not fix them here: the uv-managed environment the installer lays
# down is upstream's tested dependency set, not ours. Pip-installing
# newer versions on top, or patching the resolved lockfile, would ship a
# combination Hermes was never run against and risk breaking the agent —
# and this image's standing policy is to stay as close to upstream
# hermes-agent as possible (see the Dockerfile). The fix has to arrive
# as a Hermes release whose own dependency set resolves the fixed
# versions.
#
#   mcp 1.26.0               CVE-2026-52869 / CVE-2026-52870
#                            (both fixed in 1.27.2),
#                            CVE-2026-59950 (fixed in 1.28.1)
#   python-multipart 0.0.27  CVE-2026-53539 (fixed in 0.0.30)
#   starlette 1.0.1          CVE-2026-48818 (fixed in 1.1.0),
#                            CVE-2026-54283 (fixed in 1.3.1)
#
# Exposure in THIS image: all three packages are MCP / ASGI server-side
# components. The only server we knowingly run is the supervised
# dashboard, bound loopback-only on 127.0.0.1:9119 — the pod contract
# never exposes it, and the password-gated VNC display is the sole way
# in, so exploiting a server-side flaw first requires an authenticated
# session (or a sidecar sharing the pod's network namespace). Whether
# the dashboard server is actually built on starlette, and whether the
# agent ever binds an MCP server beyond loopback, is upstream
# implementation detail we have NOT traced — treat this block as "no
# known remote path", not "proven unreachable".
#
# Re-evaluate on EVERY HERMES_VERSION bump (renovate tracks
# NousResearch/hermes-agent in the Dockerfile): rebuild, rescan, and
# drop each ID the new release's dependency set no longer trips.
CVE-2026-52869
CVE-2026-52870
CVE-2026-59950
CVE-2026-53539
CVE-2026-48818
CVE-2026-54283
